Weekly Breach Investigation
Breach: Underminr — CDN Abuse to Bypass DNS Filtering
Analyst: Jamal Mahmoad
Date: 2026-05-28

1. Executive Summary
🚨 Underminr is a stealthy technique abusing shared CDN infrastructure to bypass protective DNS filtering.
By manipulating SNI and HTTP Host headers while using legitimate DNS responses, attackers can disguise malicious traffic behind trusted domains.
This undermines DNS‑based defenses and enables covert C2 communication, data exfiltration, VPN tunneling, and policy circumvention.

2. Attack Timeline
2018: Major cloud providers mitigate domain fronting.

2022–2025: Emergence of Underminr in advanced campaigns.

2026: ADAMnetworks publishes detailed research and detection guidance.

Exploitation Path:

User resolves a trusted domain (e.g., whatismyipaddress.com).

Connection is redirected to a malicious domain (e.g., evilsite.ai) on the same CDN edge IP.

Attackers manipulate SNI/Host headers.

Traffic appears legitimate but reaches malicious endpoints.

3. MITRE ATT&CK Mapping
Command & Control: Protocol Tunneling (T1572)

Command & Control: Abuse of External Remote Services (T1133)

Defense Evasion: Encrypted Channel / SNI Manipulation (T1573)

Exfiltration: Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol (T1048)

4. Detection Opportunities
Log Sources:

DNS query logs

TLS handshake metadata

CDN edge IP traffic

Detection Rules:

Correlate DNS queries with actual connection endpoints.

Alert on mismatches between DNS resolution and SNI.

Monitor direct connections to CDN edge IPs without DNS.

5. Recommended Mitigations
Deploy deep traffic correlation between DNS and TLS/SNI.

Enforce full proxying or traffic decryption in sensitive environments.

Block unauthorized direct‑to‑IP connections on CDN infrastructure.

Use threat intelligence feeds to identify abused domains.

Collaborate with CDN providers for coordinated mitigation.

Analyst Notes
Underminr revives the concept of domain fronting with more advanced evasion, creating a blind spot for DNS‑based defenses.
As IPv4 exhaustion drives more services onto shared infrastructure, the risk of cross‑tenant abuse will grow.
Organizations must move beyond DNS filtering alone and adopt multi‑layered traffic analysis to counter this evolving threat
